{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_3","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/zsh -lc \"sed -n '1,260p' .handoff-architect-stage-4-ai-drafting-plan-2026-04-23.md\"","aggregated_output":"# Architect plan — Stage 4 AI drafting: ship Phase 3\n\n**Locked**: 2026-04-23\n**Deployment target**: Phase 3 (baseline bootstrap at project activation + captured-reply upgrading)\n**Codex delivery**: three sequential briefs (Brief 1 → 2 → 3). Each brief gated on the prior PR merging.\n**Architecture memory**: [`~/.claude/projects/-Users-nicolas-Downloads-AS-Comms-Platform/memory/project_ai_assistant_architecture_revision_2026_04_23.md`](../../.claude/projects/-Users-nicolas-Downloads-AS-Comms-Platform/memory/project_ai_assistant_architecture_revision_2026_04_23.md)\n\n---\n\n## Architecture (locked 2026-04-23 — diverges from canon)\n\n| Tier | Canon says | We're building |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 (tone/voice) | Notion → `ai_knowledge_entries` (scope=global) | Same as canon. General Training page synced. |\n| 2 (project context) | Notion → `ai_knowledge_entries` (scope=project) | Same as canon. Project Training row body synced. **Child databases dropped from sync.** |\n| 3 (approved knowledge) | Notion child DBs → `ai_knowledge_entries` | **Moved to new `project_knowledge_entries` table in platform.** Seeded one-time from Whitebark's existing Notion child DBs, then Notion child DBs archived. |\n| 4 (thread context) | Live Stage 1 projections | Same as canon. |\n| 5 (reusable memory) | `aiDurableState` with `resolved_reply_example` + OpenAI embeddings + cosine similarity | **Unified with tier 3 — same `project_knowledge_entries` table.** No embeddings. Retrieval = SQL attribute-match + keyword. `source_kind` column distinguishes `captured_from_send` vs `hand_authored` vs `bootstrap_synthesized`. |\n\n**Other lock-ins:**\n- Single LLM vendor: Anthropic Claude Sonnet 4.6. **OpenAI is dropped entirely from the stack** (no embeddings).\n- No Gmail-history bulk ingest. Gmail is read ONCE at Phase 3 project-activation-bootstrap for existing projects that already have alias traffic, as an input to LLM synthesis — not stored directly.\n- Fallback mode = Claude still drafts a skeleton \"we don't have a specific pattern — here's a frame to fill\" with `grounding_empty` warning. NOT a deterministic template.\n- Cost tracking Phase 1: per-call token estimate in the response envelope + log line. Daily-rollup DB table deferred to post-MVP.\n- Explainability Phase 1: inline \"About this draft\" popover surfacing tier-1/2 sources (as Notion links) + response mode + warnings. No heavy sidebar.\n- Capture UX: a checkbox in the Composer at send time, labeled \"Add this reply as a canonical for this project.\" Defaults unchecked. Writes to `project_knowledge_entries` with `approved_for_ai=false` on send success.\n\n**Canon updates (architect-track PR, not Codex work):**\n- `docs/04-implementation-specs/stage-4-ai-pipeline.md` — rewrite tier-3/5 section to match the new architecture; drop OpenAI references; document the bootstrap phase.\n- `docs/01-core/decision-log.md` — add 2026-04-23 entry locking the revised architecture, marking the 2026-04-21 Q1–Q5 entry's OpenAI-as-embedding-provider line as superseded.\n- `docs/03-reference/reference-security-response.md` — remove `OPENAI_API_KEY` row; add `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`.\n\n---\n\n## Dispatch sequence\n\n| Order | Brief | Branch | Model | Effort | Unblocks |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Anthropic adapter + draft:generate + \"Draft with AI\" button + Notion-only grounding | `feat/stage-4-ai-draft-button` | GPT-5.4 | **High** | User can click Draft with AI and get a Claude-generated draft. |\n| 2 | `project_knowledge_entries` table + capture checkbox + Settings Knowledge tab + tier-3 retrieval + one-time Notion-child-DB migration | `feat/stage-4-knowledge-table` | GPT-5.4 | **High** | Captured replies start growing the KB; operator can review/approve in Settings. |\n| 3 | Per-project source-link config + LLM synthesis bootstrap job + Gmail-alias one-time ingest | `feat/stage-4-bootstrap-synthesis` | GPT-5.4 | **Extra High** | Activating a project produces a baseline KB in minutes. |\n\n**Why High (not Extra High) for Briefs 1 and 2**: each is well-scoped multi-file work but not novel in shape — Anthropic SDK usage, server action, Drizzle table, Settings tab are all standard patterns. Extra High is reserved for the genuinely novel (Brief 3's LLM-synthesis pipeline).\n\n**Parallel-work coordination**: Stage 4 AI work touches mostly new files. Migration slot `0022` is next free (0020 = ai_knowledge_entries, 0021 = gmail_message_label_ids from P0). Safe to dispatch Brief 1 alongside in-flight P0 (gmail drafts) and P3 (campaign bubble) agents — no file overlap. Brief 2's Composer edit to `inbox-composer.tsx` is in the \"safe\" list per the parallel handoff doc.\n\n---\n\n## Brief 1 — \"Draft with AI\" button with Notion-only grounding\n\n### Role + audience\n\nCodex brief. Build the Anthropic provider, orchestration service, server action, and UI button needed to produce a working AI draft grounded in tier-1 (tone) + tier-2 (project context) data that is already synced from Notion via the notion-knowledge-sync worker job.\n\n### Context in one paragraph\n\nThe Notion knowledge sync is already built and populates `ai_knowledge_entries` with `scope='global'` (general training / voice) and `scope='project'` (project row body). There is no Anthropic integration, no `draft:generate` server action, no AI-draft UI button in the production Composer, and no orchestration service. The `inbox-client-provider.tsx` has a client-side `aiDraft` state machine with placeholder methods — it currently drives only the `/inbox/states` QA showcase. This brief wires real backend behavior into that state machine.\n\n### Architecture in one paragraph\n\nA new `@as-comms/ai` package (or a new folder `apps/web/src/server/ai/`, your call — prefer folder-in-web unless the orchestration ends up shared with the worker, which for Phase 1 it doesn't) hosts the orchestration pipeline: request normalizer → retriever (SQL on `ai_knowledge_entries` scope=global + scope=project for the request's project) → prompt builder → Anthropic call → response envelope. A new provider wrapper at `packages/integrations/src/providers/anthropic.ts` owns SDK construction, retries, error taxonomy. A new server action `draftWithAiAction` on `apps/web/app/inbox/actions.ts` calls the orchestration and returns the envelope. The Composer gets a \"Draft with AI\" button that, on click, calls the action and populates the composer body with the result.\n\n### Canon touch points\n\n- Prior canon (`docs/04-implementation-specs/stage-4-ai-pipeline.md`) describes a richer tier-5 memory path and OpenAI embeddings — BOTH DROPPED per revised architecture memory. For Brief 1, tier 3 and tier 5 are absent. Retrieval stops at tier 2.\n- `D-032` (Stage 4 pipeline spec) is still the canonical shape, but tier 3/5 sections are being architecturally revised separately.\n- Grounding priority order (1 → 4) is preserved: general tone > project context > thread context (tier 4 deferred — included as raw target inbound text only, not a retrieval).\n\n### Required environment variables\n\nAdd to worker + web env. Update `.env.example` and `docs/03-reference/reference-env.md`.\n\n- `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` — Anthropic API key (admin creates at console.anthropic.com).\n- `AI_DAILY_CAP_USD` — soft-cap in USD. Default `20`. Read at startup. Surfaced as `budget_warn` in the response envelope once projected daily spend exceeds it. NOT enforced as a hard block. For Phase 1, the daily-spend rollup is a naïve in-memory counter that resets on process restart; a real persisted rollup is Phase 2.\n- `ANTHROPIC_MODEL` — default `claude-sonnet-4-6`. Override per-env for staging / dev.\n\nIf `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` is missing at draft-request time, the server action returns `mode='deterministic_fallback'` with `warnings[0].code='provider_not_configured'` and a skeleton draft. DO NOT crash the request.\n\n### Files to create / change\n\n#### 1. Anthropic provider\n\nCreate `packages/integrations/src/providers/anthropic.ts`. Must expose:\n\n- `createAnthropicClient(env: { ANTHROPIC_API_KEY: string }): AnthropicClient` — wraps `@anthropic-ai/sdk`'s `Anthropic` client with our standard error taxonomy (`provider_timeout`, `provider_rate_limited`, `provider_unavailable`). Match the error style used by `gmail.ts` / `salesforce.ts` / `notion.ts`.\n- `generateDraft(client, input): Promise<GenerateDraftResult>` — single messages.create call. Input carries `model`, `messages`, `system`, `maxTokens`, `temperature`. Returns `{ text, usage: { inputTokens, outputTokens }, stopReason, model }`. Handles retries (up to 2) on 429/5xx with exponential backoff.\n- `estimateCostUsd(usage, model): number` — simple per-model rate card. Hardcode Sonnet 4.6 input/output rates; error-log if model is unknown and return 0.\n\nAdd `@anthropic-ai/sdk` (latest stable minor) to `packages/integrations/package.json`. Match existing provider coding style — Result envelopes and error types consistent.\n\nNo live provider calls from the worker; web-side only for Phase 1.\n\n#### 2. Orchestration service\n\nCreate `apps/web/src/server/ai/` with:\n\n- `index.ts` — public export: `generateAiDraft(deps, input)`.\n- `types.ts` — zod schemas for `AiDraftRequest` (`contactId`, optional `threadCursor`, optional `operatorPrompt`, `projectId`), `AiDraftResponse` (`draft`, `mode`, `grounding[]`, `warnings[]`, `costEstimateUsd`, `providerStatus`, `draftId`).\n- `retriever.ts` — pure function `retrieveGrounding(db, { projectId, contactId })` returns `{ generalTraining: AiKnowledgeEntry | null, projectContext: AiKnowledgeEntry | null, targetInbound: CanonicalEventRecord | null }`.\n- `prompt-builder.ts` — pure function that builds the Anthropic system prompt + user message from the grounding bundle. The system prompt layers tier-1 → tier-2 in that order, with explicit section headers and instructions to preserve hierarchy. The user message includes the target inbound body (truncated to 2000 chars if larger), the operator's optional prompt, and the request to draft a reply.\n- `validator.ts` — MVP checks: reject empty drafts, reject drafts that literally echo the tier-1 text verbatim (>50% overlap), reject drafts with obvious template-variable leakage (`{NAME}`, `{EMAIL}` still present). On failure, fall back to skeleton.\n- `fallback-builder.ts` — pure function that builds a skeleton draft given `{ inbound, projectContext, warning }`. Output is a short first-person \"Hi [first name if known]\" paragraph acknowledging receipt + a sentence naming the topic + a closing invite. Example when `warning='grounding_empty'`:\n  ```\n  Hi {firstName},\n  Thanks for reaching out about {topicGuess}. I don't have specific guidance to share on this yet — let me look into it and get back to you soon.\n  Best,\n  ```\n- `draft-generator.ts` — orchestrator that composes retriever → prompt-builder → Anthropic call → validator → envelope.\n- `explainability.ts` — shapes the `grounding[]` array in the response from the retrieval result (each entry: `{ tier, sourceProvider, sourceId, sourceUrl, title }`).\n- `cost-counter.ts` — naïve in-memory daily cost counter. `record(costUsd): void`, `isOverBudget(): boolean`. Process-local only for Phase 1.\n\nCo-locate tests under `apps/web/test/server/ai/*.test.ts` using the repo's existing Vitest conventions.\n\n#### 3. Server action\n\nEdit `apps/web/app/inbox/actions.ts` — add:\n\n```ts\nexport async function draftWithAiAction(\n  input: AiDraftRequestPayload\n): Promise<UiResult<AiDraftResponseVm>>\n```\n\nWire it to `generateAiDraft` with the request-scoped Stage 1 DB handle. Return the envelope as a `UiResult` so the UI can surface warnings uniformly. Use the repo's existing `UiResult` shape — follow `sendComposerAction` as the reference pattern.\n\nAdd a rate limiter — max 5 concurrent AI draft requests per authenticated user (Phase 1 is single-operator anyway; this is defensive). Use a simple Map-based counter; a real limiter is post-MVP.\n\n#### 4. Composer UI — dynamic button (Draft / Fill / Reprompt)\n\nEdit `apps/web/app/inbox/_components/inbox-composer.tsx`:\n\n- Add a sparkles-icon button in the composer toolbar, to the left of the attachment paperclip.\n- **Button label is dynamic based on composer body state:**\n  - Body empty (or whitespace only) → label \"Draft with AI\", mode `draft`\n  - Body has content → label \"Fill with AI\", mode `fill`\n  - Button disabled ONLY while AI is actively generating (loading). It is NOT disabled when body is non-empty.\n- **On click:**\n  - Mode `draft`: call `draftWithAiAction` with `{ contactId, projectId, threadCursor, mode: 'draft', operatorPrompt: undefined }`\n  - Mode `fill`: call `draftWithAiAction` with `{ contactId, projectId, threadCursor, mode: 'fill', operatorPrompt: <composerBodyText> }`. The operator's typed text is consumed as directive; final draft REPLACES the composer body (operator intent is expressed, not preserved verbatim).\n- **After any successful draft insertion**, surface a **reprompt row** below the composer body:\n  - A compact text input + \"Reprompt\" button.\n  - On click: call `draftWithAiAction` with `{ ...prevRequest, mode: 'reprompt', previousDraft: currentDraft, repromptDirection: <inputValue> }`.\n  - Clears the reprompt input on success; draft body updates in place.\n  - No hard cap on reprompt count. Server logs reprompt count per draft for tuning.\n- Next to the reprompt input, add an **\"About this draft\"** link (visible when `aiDraft.status === 'inserted'`). Clicking opens a shadcn **Dialog modal** (not a popover) showing developer/architect-oriented detail: raw prompt text (collapsible), grounding rows (tier + source + Notion URL), model params (name, temperature, input/output tokens), cost estimate, reprompt chain (list of `{ direction, resultingDraft }` from the full session), and typed warnings. Not polished for operator reassurance — this surface is for tuning the AI, not reassuring users.\n- **On `mode='deterministic_fallback'`** from the server (any failure path, including `grounding_empty`): insert the skeleton draft; render a warning banner above the composer; reprompt row still available.\n- **On `warnings[].code='grounding_contradiction'`** (Fill mode only): Claude still obeys the operator's directive and produces a draft, but the envelope flags the contradiction. UI renders a warning banner: \"Your directive appears to contradict the project context (<surfaced contradiction summary>). If this is correct, reprompt to confirm or update project docs; otherwise, edit the draft manually.\"\n\nExtend `apps/web/app/inbox/_components/inbox-client-provider.tsx`:\n\n- Change `aiDraft` state to carry: `mode`, `grounding[]`, `warnings[]`, `costEstimateUsd`, `draftId`, `repromptChain: Array<{ direction, draft }>`.\n- Update `startAiGeneration`, `repromptAi`, `insertAiDraft` signatures to carry the full request + envelope.\n\nCreate `apps/web/app/inbox/_components/about-this-draft.tsx` — shadcn `Dialog` modal. Sections: Grounding sources, Prompt preview (collapsible), Model params, Cost estimate, Reprompt chain (if non-empty), Warnings. Dev-oriented; no animations or reassurance copy.\n\n**Empty-grounding fallback shape:** the skeleton draft produced when both tier 1 and tier 2 return empty MUST include clear placeholder slots using square-bracket notation (e.g. `[add the specific answer here]`, `[fill the project-specific detail]`). Operators must know exactly where to intervene. NOT a generic \"thanks, we'll get back to you\" template.\n\n#### 5. States showcase\n\nUpdate `apps/web/app/inbox/states/page.tsx` to exercise the new response-mode paths via the same client state — no extra server wiring. Ensure the Draft with AI / Generating / Inserted / Unavailable / Error states still render correctly with the extended payload shape.\n\n#### 6. Tests\n\n- `packages/integrations/test/anthropic-provider.test.ts` — unit tests for the provider wrapper (error taxonomy, retry, cost estimation).\n- `apps/web/test/server/ai/retriever.test.ts` — retrieves general + project entries correctly, handles missing project, handles empty DB.\n- `apps/web/test/server/ai/prompt-builder.test.ts` — snapshot test of the assembled prompt for a representative input (Whitebark).\n- `apps/web/test/server/ai/validator.test.ts` — rejects empty / template-leaking / tier-echoing drafts.\n- `apps/web/test/server/ai/draft-generator.test.ts` — full pipeline against a mocked Anthropic client; covers `draft`, `grounding_empty`, `provider_not_configured`, `provider_timeout` → fallback.\n- `apps/web/tests/unit/inbox-composer-ai-button.test.tsx` — button renders, disabled when body non-empty, click triggers state transition. (Use the same React Testing Library patterns as existing composer tests.)\n\n#### 7. Docs\n\n- `docs/03-reference/reference-env.md` — add `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`, `AI_DAILY_CAP_USD`, `ANTHROPIC_MODEL`. Remove `OPENAI_API_KEY` deferral line.\n- `docs/03-reference/reference-security-response.md` — same swap.\n- `docs/04-implementation-specs/stage-4-ai-pipeline.md` — DO NOT edit in this brief. Architect-track canon refresh follows in a separate PR.\n\n### Acceptance / definition of done\n\n- CI green (typecheck, lint, unit tests).\n- With `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` set and `ai_knowledge_entries` populated for a project via the existing Notion sync, clicking \"Draft with AI\" in the Composer produces a non-empty, AS-voice draft inserted into the composer body within ~6 seconds p95.\n- With `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` unset, clicking the button produces a skeleton draft with a visible warning banner. No crash, no 500.\n- With `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` set but an unknown project (no `ai_knowledge_entries` for scope=project), the draft is generated using only tier-1 tone + the target inbound. A `grounding_empty` warning surfaces.\n- The \"About this draft\" popover opens and shows at least tier-1 and (when present) tier-2 sources with clickable Notion URLs.\n- No change to the Composer send flow (send button works identically).\n- The token usage on a typical draft (20-event thread, 500-char inbound, Whitebark context) is sanity-checked under 4000 total tokens per call.\n\n### What NOT to do\n\n- Do NOT add `project_knowledge_entries`, canonical-reply retrieval, capture checkbox, or Settings UI — those belong to Brief 2.\n- Do NOT install or reference `openai` or any embedding library.\n- Do NOT write to `aiDurableState` — tier-5 memory is not in Phase 1.\n- Do NOT touch `packages/integrations/src/providers/gmail.ts`, `packages/integrations/src/capture-services/gmail.ts`, or `packages/db/schema/tables.ts` gmail_message_details — those are owned by in-flight P0 Codex agent.\n- Do NOT touch `apps/web/app/inbox/_lib/selectors.ts` `campaignHeadlineAndBody` — owned by in-flight P3 Codex agent.\n- Do NOT modify the `/inbox/states` showcase beyond what's needed to keep it rendering; it is a design-review surface, not a test harness.\n- Do NOT add streaming / token-by-token UI. One-shot response is canon.\n- Do NOT introduce a cron or background worker for drafts; drafts are on-demand per operator click.\n\n### Recommended model + effort\n\n**GPT-5.4 — High.**\n\nRationale: touches a new integration provider, orchestration modules across a new folder, a server action, UI in the Composer, client-provider state changes, and tests — roughly the scope of the composer PRs (#80, #82). Not Extra High because the shape is conventional (SDK wrapper, prompt builder, popover) and the canon is clear. If the Codex agent hits confusion on the `UiResult` envelope shape or the client-provider state integration, it can reference existing composer/send patterns.\n\n---\n\n## Brief 2 — Outline (drafted after Brief 1 merges)\n\n### Scope\n\n- Migration `0022_project_knowledge_entries.sql` + Drizzle schema.\n- Table columns: `id`, `project_id`, `kind` (`canonical_reply` | `snippet` | `pattern`), `issue_type`, `volunteer_stage`, `question_summary`, `reply_strategy`, `masked_example`, `source_kind` (`hand_authored` | `captured_from_send` | `bootstrap_synthesized`), `approved_for_ai`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `last_reviewed_at`, `created_by_user_id`, `source_event_id` (nullable — links to the canonical outbound event if `source_kind='captured_from_send'`), `metadata` jsonb.\n- Retrieval extension: tier-3 module that queries `project_knowledge_entries` filtered by `project_id` and `approved_for_ai=true`, ranks by simple keyword/attribute match against the target inbound, returns top N entries of each kind (e.g., 3 canonicals + 2 snippets + 2 patterns).\n- Prompt-builder extension: inject tier-3 entries as a new prompt section after tier-2, formatted as structured examples with `Issue Type`, `Question Summary`, `Reply Strategy`, `Masked Example`.\n- Capture flow: add a \"Add as canonical for this project\" checkbox to the Composer send card (near the Send button). On send success (server action callback), if checked, issue a post-send server action `captureKnowledgeFromSendAction` that writes a row with `source_kind='captured_from_send'`, `approved_for_ai=false`, `source_event_id=<sent event id>`. The captured row's `kind` defaults to `canonical_reply`; operator can reclassify in Settings.\n- Settings → Projects → [project] → Knowledge tab: table view + inline edit + approved-for-AI toggle. Read-only columns: created, source_kind, question_summary. Editable columns: issue_type (select), volunteer_stage (select), reply_strategy (textarea), masked_example (textarea), approved_for_ai (toggle). No \"create new\" form in Phase 2 — entries enter only via capture.\n- One-time ops script: `apps/worker/src/ops/migrate-notion-child-dbs-to-project-knowledge.ts`. Reads Whitebark's (and any other populated projects') Canonical Replies / Approved Snippets / Support Patterns Notion databases, maps each row into a `project_knowledge_entries` row with `source_kind='hand_authored'` and `approved_for_ai=true` (since they were human-curated). Runs once via `pnpm ops:migrate-notion-to-knowledge`.\n- Extend the Notion sync job to NOT re-ingest child databases (it currently doesn't; just confirm and document).\n\n### Recommended model + effort\n\n**GPT-5.4 — High.** Standard shape: migration + schema + retrieval SQL + UI Settings tab + ops script. Novel piece is the ops-script classification heuristics for mapping Notion rows to our table, but that's linear logic, not algorithmic.\n\n### Gated on\n\nBrief 1 merged. No parallel conflict with P0 / P3 (those will have long since merged by the time Brief 2 is ready).\n\n---\n\n## Brief 3 — Outline (drafted after Brief 2 merges)\n\n### Scope\n\n- **Source-link management UI**: per-project Settings panel adds a \"Knowledge Sources\" list. Each row = `{ label, url, kind }` where `kind ∈ { public_project_page, volunteer_homepage, training_site, gmail_alias_history, other }`. CRUD via Settings.\n- **New table `project_knowledge_source_links`**: stores the above. Migration `0023`.\n- **Bootstrap job**: new worker task `bootstrap-project-knowledge`. Triggered manually from Settings via a \"Generate baseline knowledge\" button (per-project). Sequence:\n  1. Read source links for the project.\n  2. For each `kind ∈ { public_project_page, volunteer_homepage, training_site, other }`: fetch the URL, extract main text content (use a lightweight readability-style extractor — consider `@mozilla/readability` + `jsdom`). Chunk to ~2000-token segments.\n  3. For `kind = gmail_alias_history`: query `canonical_events` for outbound + inbound events on the project's alias, bounded to last 24 months. Flatten into a condensed thread-pair digest (inbound → outbound text pairs, truncated).\n  4. LLM synthesis pass 1 (Anthropic): \"extract topics\" — produce a list of distinct question topics + volunteer-facing concerns observed.\n  5. LLM synthesis pass 2 (Anthropic): for each topic, produce canonical/snippet/pattern candidates in the shape of `project_knowledge_entries`. Output JSON with `kind`, `issue_type`, `volunteer_stage`, `question_summary`, `reply_strategy`, `masked_example`.\n  6. Write candidates to `project_knowledge_entries` with `source_kind='bootstrap_synthesized'`, `approved_for_ai=false`. Attach the synthesis run id in `metadata` so admin can trace provenance.\n- **Run status UI**: the bootstrap button shows progress (queued → fetching sources → synthesizing → writing entries → done) + a summary of entries created. Not real-time; 30-second poll is fine.\n- **Cost tracking**: bootstrap runs can be expensive (multi-call LLM synthesis). Per-run token usage + cost estimate surfaced in the run status and logged.\n- **Safety rails**: reject bootstrap runs for projects with zero source links. Require admin confirmation if `project_knowledge_entries` already has >50 rows for this project (prevents accidental re-synthesis clobbering curated entries).\n- **Tests**: fetcher unit tests (mocked HTTP), synthesis prompt snapshot tests, end-to-end happy-path with fake Anthropic client, error-mode tests (timeout, partial failure, over-budget).\n\n### Recommended model + effort\n\n**GPT-5.4 — Extra High.** Genuinely novel: LLM-synthesis pipeline with multi-pass prompting, content extraction, chunking, failure modes under partial source availability, admin-facing run status UI. This is the brief that warrants full effort.\n\n### Gated on\n\nBrief 2 merged (needs `project_knowledge_entries`). No parallel conflict expected.\n\n---\n\n## Environment + rollout steps (user, not Codex)\n\n**Before Brief 1 merges:**\n\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
